    "# Automatic Classification of Sleep States\n",
    "\n",
    "Mammalian sleep consists of 3 distinct brain states: Wakefulness, REM (Rapid eye movement) sleep, and NREM (non-REM) sleep. These 3 states can be identified through inspection of EEG (electroencephalogram) and EMG (electromyogram) data. A major bottleneck in sleep research is that hours of sleep recordings have to be manually annotated by experts, a very time consuming process. Here, we will use deep neural networks to automatically classify sleep states based on EEG and EMG data obtained from mice. The data used for this project were made available by the dedicated researchers at the [Chung Lab](https://chunglab.med.upenn.edu/) and [Weber Lab](https://www.med.upenn.edu/weberlab/) at the University of Pennsylvania Perelman School of Medicine.\n",
    "\n"
   ]

    "## 1. A look at the data\n",
    "\n",
    "### EEG and EMG\n",
    "- EEG measures the electrical activity of the brain. More specifically, it measures voltage fluctuations resulting from ionic currents in neurons. More details on the origins of EEG can be found in this [video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bmt89hHyxuM).\n",
    "- EMG measures the electric potential generated by muscle cells.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Sleep recordings\n",
    "All the sleep recordings (training and test data) used for this project can be downloaded [here](https://upenn.box.com/s/ibbmqfcqsnqtbfwde5r869cl87k3zqeb).\n",
    "\n",
    "Each folder contains one sleep recording:\n",
    "* A typical recording is titled XXX_XXXXXXn1: (ex) c28_032518n1\n",
    "    * The characters before the underscore represent a unique identifier for each mouse.\n",
    "    * The numbers after the underscore denote the date on which the recording took place.\n",
    "* Each recording folder contains the following files:\n",
    "    * EEG.mat - Binary matlab file containing parietal EEG sampled at 1000 Hz\n",
    "    * EEG2.mat - Prefrontal EEG sampled at 1000 Hz\n",
    "    * EMG.mat - EMG recorded from neck at 1000 Hz\n",
    "    * 3_remidx_XXX_XXXXXXn1.txt - Text file containing annotations for each 2.5 s window of the recording\n",
    "        * 0 - Undefined/Artefact\n",
    "        * 1 - REM\n",
    "        * 2 - Wake\n",
    "        * 3 - NREM\n",
    "* Each recording is typically 8 hours or 24 hours long\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### *rempropensity.py*\n",
    "This repository contains a script titled *rempropensity.py*. This script was originally written for use in another [research project](https://github.com/parksu111/REM_regulation) and contains many functions that help processing the sleep recording data."
   ]

    "## 2. Basics of mouse sleep state classification\n",
    "\n",
    "Each of the three sleep states (REM, NREM, Wake) can be identified by examining the parietal EEG and EMG. The following image was taken from [Park and Weber 2020](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2020.01662/). \n",
    "\n",
    "![Sleep states](img/state_example.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "* REM sleep is characterized by low-amplitude high-frequency (5-12 Hz) oscillations in the EEG along with a flat EMG due to muscle atonia.\n",
    "* NREM sleep exhibits high-amplitude low-frequency (0.5-4.5 Hz) oscillations.\n",
    "* Wake is characterized by high-frequency oscillations in the EEG together with high activity in the EMG due to movement.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's see if we can find a similar pattern in our data:"

    "Clearly, the 3 states exhibit distinct features in the EEG and EMG. \n",
    "\n",
    "We can also spot differences between REM and NREM by examining the spectral density of the EEG. The Fourier transform takes a signal (the EEG waves) and transforms it from the time domain to the freuquency domain (For an intuitive understanding, watch this great [video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=spUNpyF58BY) by 3Blue1Brown).\n",
    "\n",
    "Below, we will go through a subset of our recordings and calculate the average spectral density during REM and NREM."

    "# Lists to store spectral density\n",
    "remSpec = []\n",
    "nremSpec = []\n",
    "\n",
    "twin = 3\n",
    "\n",
    "recordings2 = recordings[0::5]\n",
    "\n",
    "for rec in recordings2:\n",
    "    # Find sampling rate, overlap, window size for FT\n",
    "    sr = rp.get_snr(ppath, rec)\n",
    "    nbin = int(np.round(sr)*2.5)\n",
    "    dt = nbin * 1/sr\n",
    "    nwin = np.round(twin*sr)\n",
    "    EEG = np.squeeze(so.loadmat(os.path.join(ppath, rec, 'EEG.mat'))['EEG']).astype('float')\n",
    "    # Load recording and process\n",
    "    M,S = rp.load_stateidx(ppath, rec)\n",
    "    Mvec = rp.nts(M)\n",
    "    Mtup = rp.vecToTup(Mvec, 0)\n",
    "    # Find nrem to rem transitions\n",
    "    nrt_locs = rp.nrt_locations(Mtup)\n",
    "    # Loop through all REM-NREM cycles\n",
    "    cnt2 = 0\n",
    "    while cnt2 < len(nrt_locs)-1:\n",
    "        # One REM-NREM cycle\n",
    "        sub = Mtup[nrt_locs[cnt2]:nrt_locs[cnt2+1]]\n",
    "        # Find indices of each state\n",
    "        states = np.array([x[0] for x in sub])\n",
    "        remInds = np.where((states=='R'))[0]\n",
    "        nremInds = np.where((states=='N'))[0]\n",
    "        remSeqs = rp.stateSeq(sub, remInds)\n",
    "        nremSeqs = rp.stateSeq(sub, nremInds)\n",
    "        # Calculate spectral density\n",
    "        subRemSp = []\n",
    "        subNremSp = []\n",
    "        subWakeSp = []\n",
    "        for s in remSeqs:\n",
    "            if len(s)*nbin>=nwin:\n",
    "                b = int((s[-1]+1)*nbin)\n",
    "                sup = list(range(int(s[0]*nbin), b))\n",
    "                if sup[-1]>len(EEG):\n",
    "                    sup = list(range(int(s[0]*nbin), len(EEG)))\n",
    "                if len(sup) >= nwin:\n",
    "                    Pow,F = rp.power_spectrum(EEG[sup], nwin, 1/sr)\n",
    "                    subRemSp.append(Pow)\n",
    "        for s in nremSeqs:\n",
    "            if len(s)*nbin>=nwin:\n",
    "                b = int((s[-1]+1)*nbin)\n",
    "                sup = list(range(int(s[0]*nbin), b))\n",
    "                if sup[-1]>len(EEG):\n",
    "                    sup = list(range(int(s[0]*nbin), len(EEG)))\n",
    "                if len(sup) >= nwin:\n",
    "                    Pow,F = rp.power_spectrum(EEG[sup], nwin, 1/sr)\n",
    "                    subNremSp.append(Pow)\n",
    "        ifreq = np.where(F<=20) #Only inspect below 20 Hz\n",
    "        sremSpec = np.array([x[ifreq] for x in subRemSp])\n",
    "        snremSpec = np.array([x[ifreq] for x in subNremSp])\n",
    "        #Calculate avg. spec. den. for given REM-NREM cycle\n",
    "        if len(sremSpec)>0:\n",
    "            avgRemSpec = np.mean(sremSpec, axis=0)\n",
    "            remSpec.append(avgRemSpec)\n",
    "        if len(snremSpec)>0:\n",
    "            avgNremSpec = np.mean(snremSpec, axis=0)\n",
    "            nremSpec.append(avgNremSpec)\n",
    "        cnt2+=1\n",
    "    print(rec)    "
   ]

    "The typical procedure of annotating a sleep recording is as follows:\n",
    "* All bins in which there is a lot of EMG activity (high amplitude) are labelled as 'Wake'\n",
    "* Of the bins that are not labelled as 'Wake':\n",
    "    * Bins dominated by oscillations in the theta range are labelled as REM\n",
    "    * Bins dominated by oscillations in the delta range are labelled as NREM"

    "## 3. Different approaches to interpreting the data\n",
    "\n",
    "Although EEG and EMG data are both time series data (numbers representing electric potential changes over time), it makes sense to think of classifying sleep states as an image classification task for 2 reasons:\n",
    "1. When looking at the EEG and EMG waves for sleep-scoring, humans don't see them as a series of numbers. Rather, they notice shapes in the graphs (ex, low-amplitude, high-frequency oscillations for REM).\n",
    "2. Signals can be turned into spectograms.\n",
    "\n",
    "We will tackle the problem of sleep state classification using both approaches. The details will be gone over in different notebooks here:\n",
    "\n",
    "* [Sleep-scoring as an image classification task](https://github.com/parksu111/mouse_sleep_auto_classification/blob/main/img_classification.ipynb)\n",
    "* Sleep-scoring as a digital signal classification task\n"
